It looks that `[ID, Name, Nickname]` are value types. In this case `*ngFor` just uses their values without binding to the original variables.
If you still need binding, you should consider transforming them to reference types.

For example you could put them into the object, like person or options and iterate object properties using `KeyValuePipe`:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/41396435/how-to-iterate-object-keys-using-ngfor

    options: {[key: number]: string} = {ID: &#39;1&#39;, Name: &#39;bar&#39;, Nickname: &#39;foo&#39;};
    
    &lt;div *ngFor=&quot;let item of options | keyvalue&quot;&gt;

In Angular 6.1 the KeyValuePipe was introduced which allows you to iterate object properties:

    &lt;div *ngFor=&quot;let item of object | keyvalue&quot;&gt;
      {{item.key}}:{{item.value}}
    &lt;/div&gt;

Docs: https://angular.io/api/common/KeyValuePipe

The array `[ID, Name, Nickname]` contains the values of the three properties, not their references. The two-way binding will modify the array items instead of the original properties (for that to work, you must refer to the items by their index and track the array by index, as shown in [this answer][1]).

To achieve two-way binding of the component properties, you could use an array of property names, and refer to each property with `this[prop]`:

    &lt;mat-form-field *ngFor=&quot;let prop of [&#39;ID&#39;, &#39;Name&#39;, &#39;Nickname&#39;]&quot;&gt;
      &lt;input [(ngModel)]=&quot;this[prop]&quot; ... &gt;
      ...
    &lt;/mat-form-field&gt;

See [this stackblitz][2] for a demo.


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/40315703/1009922
  [2]: https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-ze2gqb?file=src%2Fapp%2Fapp.component.html

